article.description: Trina Frierson scored 27 points and pulled down 11 rebounds to lead a flu-ridden No. 12 Louisiana Tech to a 94-65 victory over Mississippi State on Sunday.
article.headline: Frierson scores 27 to lead Techsters
article.linkText: LaTech overcomes flu to rout Mississippi State
article.story: RUSTON, La. -- Trina Frierson scored 27 points and pulled down 11 rebounds to lead a flu-ridden No. 12 Louisiana Tech to a 94-65 victory over Mississippi State on Sunday. Frierson scored 15 of her points in the first half, and finished 13-of-24 from the floor. She also contributed two steals and an assist. "She did a great job in this game of going inside and attacking more with a power game rather than just hitting that 10-to-15 foot jumper that she usually relies on," coach Kurt Budke said. "He wanted me to be more aggressive and get to the foul line more and that's what I tried to do. I don't want to be just a one-dimensional player," Frierson said. The Lady Techsters had five double-figures scorers, despite a run of flu and finishing a demanding four-game schedule over eight days. "This was a good win for us because we have had several players sick with the flu, plus another dealing with a wisdom tooth," Budke said. Next up for the Techsters is No. 7 Penn State on Dec. 21. On Sunday, Erica Smith-Taylor added 14 points for the Lady Techsters (6-1). Amber Obaze and Amisha Carter had 13 apiece and Lakiste Barkus 12. Seneca Anderson led Mississippi State (2-4) with 18 points. Tan White and Tiania Burns added 13 apiece, and Mamie McKinney had 12 rebounds. Louisiana Tech led 43-38 in rebounding and had 19 assists to Mississippi State's 13. The Techsters led 14-4 after the first five minutes and led 49-25 by halftime. In the last two and a half minutes of that half, Tech scored six unanswered points, four back-to-back by Smith-Taylor. Louisiana Tech had three double digit scorers by halftime. Frierson had 15, Carter 13 and Smith-Taylor 10. "Their quickness is unbelievable and they've got tremendous depth. They don't lose much at all when they go to their bench," said Lady Bulldogs coach Sharon Fanning. "They've got a lot of weapons."
